d.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2841<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/8/03 2:53:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  What if we could see Alien Worlds?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://209.247.51.235/projects/ezboard/ezboard_userimages/amagickaljourney/images/face_with_dragons_in_front.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Imagine for a moment that we have massive telescopes in space and our astronomers have found living Alien Worlds circling other stars. The first pictures were blurry but now we have crystal clarity. Some planets have civilisations not totally unlike our own and much of what we see we can't understand. A lot of it is frightening. Is the human psyche prepared for what we might discover? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A> at: 1/8/03 2:54:51 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tmayes1999>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 166<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/8/03 4:27:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if we could see Alien Worlds?</span><hr size=1> This would result in serious Atteampts at both both robotic, and crewed Interstellar spaceflight being made.<br>
Tim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2847<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/8/03 5:21:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if we could see Alien Worlds?</span><hr size=1> Perhaps. I hope so. It could also make us more secular. Especially if we percieve a threat. Seeing cultures totally different to our own would be unsettling to some. Suppose we identify a race of creatures who are constantly at war and have advanced spaceflight capability. They may even have cannibal tendencies. It might be quite a shock to those academics who assume all intelligent Aliens to be peaceloving reflections of our own ideals. <br>
The physical appearance of other sentient beings combined with their incomprehensible cultural differences would understandably set off alarm bells in the military. On the plus side it might unite humanity in an effort to make certain we are never caught off guard. They might be visiting us first. I wonder if we could steal their technological inventions by watching from afar. One thing which would terrify me is discovering they already had telescopes trained on us. That's the stuff of nightmares. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1775<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/8/03 8:59:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if we could see Alien Worlds?</span><hr size=1> 2025 AD<br>
Astronomers using the 'Carl Sagan' deep space observatory platform discovered an alien civilization orbiting a star just 48 light years distant.  The astronomer, Dr. John Watson said that they appear to be a bipedal hominid much like us.  Their technological level appears to be analogous to mid-19th century europe.<br>
<br>
2050 AD<br>
It's been 25 years since the discovery of alien life and a sentient species, and on that anniversary the launch of a manned mission to that planet for first contact.  The prototype starship, named Challenger, and using a new type of propulsion that has been developed after 25 years of intensive R&amp;D...<br>
<br>
2100 AD Earth Calendar<br>
After 50 years of travel at near light speed, the first starship Challenger has entered the alien solar system.  They immediately detected large amounts of radio transmissions from the new world.  The alien's language has the onboard linguists mystified.<br>
<br>
As the Challenger approaches the planet, she comes under heavy radar scan.  The Challenger crew detect another spaceship approaching at high relative speed.  It seems the alien's have developed a crude spaceship that is propelling itself along by detonating nuclear explosions behind it.  The Challenger's Captain sends the pre-recorded greeting developed by Earth's scientists... a moment later the first particle beam strikes the starships hull.  An emergency signal is dispatch to Earth... which will take 50 years  before anyone hears... a second beam strikes, this one cuts the challenger in two...<br>
<br>
2200 AD<br>
Earth Force leaves Earth orbit... mission - to destroy the enemy homeworld... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 669<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/8/03 5:10:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if we could see Alien Worlds?</span><hr size=1> PO brings up a vibrant point about how observing an alien species could unhinge our view of the universe.  Many people seem to have this idea that only us humans are savage, war mongering beasts and that an alien intelligence would somehow be more benevolent and wise and could guide us to salvation.  I've never really bought that viewpoint, I think there's a great potential that we could see a vicious alien species out there killing each other.  Sure, civilizations tend to become a bit more benevolent and &quot;wiser&quot; as time goes on but I don't think it's always a given that a civilization will completely shed its savage nature.  Anyways, I think I'll be staying off any ship called &quot;Challenger.&quot;   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 1/8/03 5:14:24 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2852<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/9/03 6:54:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if we could see Alien Worlds?</span><hr size=1> That was a great story Zaph. Ironically, it could just as easily have been a story told by Alien bipeds about discovering us as it was a story about us discovering Alien bipeds. I enjoyed the tale. Its original and gives a new perspective on nuclear rocket technology.<br>
I expect that by the time the Earth fleet reaches that system it will be met by a similar fleet coming the other way. Now that they know about us they will no doubt vamp up their own spacecraft program. With the war on home territory they have an extra 50 years to construct warships as ours are in transit. Attacking another system would be very difficult. Especially after alerting them to our existance. I wonder if they managed to sift anything out of the Challengers wreckage. This one first contact could take centuries of focused attention to survive, if we survive it. A war over such distance could even last several millenia. It would become a new age of human history. Comparable to the Age of Rome or even the Iron age. Other exploration would be put on hold until the feud was settled one way or another.<br>
<br>
